    "narrative": "**Rough Night: Model Goes 0-3 on Unders in Opening Day Chaos**\n\n**MEDIUM CONFIDENCE REVIEW**\n\nThe medium tier went 0-3, losing all three under plays in what turned out to be a slugfest-heavy opening day slate.\n\nTwo of these were catastrophic misses that demand explanation. **White Sox at Brewers** projected 7.5 runs but finished at 16 \u2014 an 8.5-run miss. The pregame setup looked solid: both starters had respectable expected metrics (3.85 and 4.08 xFIP), and we had 18 mph winds blowing in from center field in 37-degree weather. That's typically a pitcher's paradise. What the model missed: either the bullpens completely imploded after the starters exited, or the cold weather affected pitcher grip and command more than it suppressed offense. When you see an 8-run miss with strong wind blowing in, something broke down beyond what the pregame data captured.\n\n**Pirates at Mets** was even worse \u2014 projected 7.7, finished at 18, a 10.3-run gap. The starting pitching matchup looked excellent (3.75 and 3.12 xFIP), and we were in a neutral dome environment. This one's harder to explain with the available data. The pregame indicators genuinely supported this call. Either we're seeing opening day rust from pitchers who didn't get full spring ramp-ups, or the bullpens were historically bad. Without pitch-by-pitch data, this looks like the model got caught in genuine variance on a day when scoring exploded across the board.\n\nThe **Tigers-Padres under** (projected 7.5, actual 10) was a smaller 2.5-run miss \u2014 that's within normal variance for totals modeling.\n\n**WHAT TO WATCH**\n\nOpening day produced three overs in three games, all with solid starting pitching indicators. If this is a league-wide trend of bullpens being unprepared or umpires squeezing the zone less than spring training, we may need to adjust our baseline run environment assumptions until the data stabilizes over the first two weeks.",
